"""
mkt-christ | Zechariah | chapters 8–13
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-zechariah-8-13.py

Deutero-Zechariah (chs 9–14) is one of the most cited OT sections in the Passion
narratives. Key NT fulfillments: 9:9 (triumphal entry), 11:12-13 (30 silver pieces),
12:10 (pierced one), 13:7 (strike the shepherd). Ch 8 closes Proto-Zechariah with
restoration promises read typologically as eschatological/ecclesiological fulfillment.

Ch 9 v9 and ch 12 v10 already present in output — merge_comm skips them.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent


def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / layer / f"{book}.json"
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}


def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / layer / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")


def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html
    return existing


ZECHARIAH = {
    "8": {
        "1": "<p>The messenger formula <em>wayyehi debar-YHWH</em> opens a fresh oracle cluster. Ch 8 gathers ten promises (vv. 2, 3, 4, 6, 7, 9, 14, 19, 20, 23), each introduced by <em>koh amar YHWH tzva&rsquo;ot</em>. The repetitive structure signals covenant solemnity. In Christ this pattern of divine promise-making reaches its fulfillment: 2 Cor 1:20 declares that in Jesus &ldquo;all the promises of God find their Yes,&rdquo; the accumulated <em>koh amar</em> declarations of the prophets ratified in the incarnate Word.</p>",
        "2": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s <em>qin&rsquo;ah gedolah</em> (great jealousy) for Zion echoes the covenant love of a husband who will not share his bride. The divine <em>chemah</em> (fury/heat) is the necessary inverse of that love — not arbitrary wrath but the burning of absolute fidelity. Jesus&rsquo; weeping over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41-44) and his lament over the hen gathering chicks (Matt 23:37) are the incarnate expression of this same jealous love, now anguished at rejection.</p>",
        "3": "<p>YHWH promises to return to Zion and dwell in Jerusalem. <em>Qir&rsquo;at ha-emet</em> (faithful city / city of truth) and <em>har ha-qodesh</em> (holy mountain) describe what Jerusalem will become through divine presence. John 1:14 announces the ultimate fulfillment: the Word &ldquo;tabernacled&rdquo; (<em>eskēnōsen</em>) among us in flesh. The faithful city is eschatologically realized in the New Jerusalem (Rev 21:2-3) where YHWH&rsquo;s dwelling is with humanity permanently.</p>",
        "4": "<p>Old men and women sitting with staffs in Jerusalem&rsquo;s streets depicts security, longevity, and communal flourishing — the opposite of the silence and desolation of exile. The image is shalom embodied in the aged. Jesus&rsquo; healing of the elderly (Luke 13:16, the bent woman; John 5:5, the 38-year invalid) anticipates the restoration of full human dignity promised here. The eschatological city of Rev 21-22 knows no more curse of aging and death.</p>",
        "5": "<p>Children playing in the streets complete the shalom tableau: youth and age together signify a community unafraid, with a future. Jesus&rsquo; welcoming of children (Mark 10:13-16) and his declaration that the kingdom belongs to such as these inverts the social hierarchy and points toward the new creation where children play safely &mdash; the lion lying down with the lamb (Isa 11:6-9).</p>",
        "6": "<p>The rhetorical question &ldquo;Is it too wonderful for the remnant?&rdquo; (NRSV) expresses divine irony: what seems impossible to weary post-exilic survivors is entirely possible for YHWH. The same logic structures the gospel: the resurrection is the supreme instance of divine possibility overturning human impossibility. Luke 1:37 (<em>ouk adunatēsei para tou theou pan rhēma</em>, &ldquo;nothing will be impossible with God&rdquo;) applies Gabriel&rsquo;s word to the virgin conception, but the logic has prophetic roots in texts like this.</p>",
        "7": "<p>Rescue from &ldquo;the land of the sunrise&rdquo; and &ldquo;the land of the sunset&rdquo; — east and west — is a merism for universal diaspora restoration. The New Exodus imagery governs the promise. Jesus as the one who gathers the scattered (John 11:52: &ldquo;to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad&rdquo;) fulfills this spatial merism. The church as gathered diaspora (1 Pet 1:1) embodies the ongoing fulfillment.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The covenant formula <em>wehāyū lî le&rsquo;am wa&rsquo;anî ehteyh lahem le&rsquo;lohim</em> (&ldquo;they will be my people and I will be their God&rdquo;) is the theological spine of the Sinai covenant (Exod 6:7; Lev 26:12), renewed in Jer 31:33 and Ezek 36:28. Its double qualification &mdash; &ldquo;in faithfulness and righteousness&rdquo; &mdash; points toward the New Covenant. Heb 8:10 cites Jer 31 as fulfilled in Christ; 2 Cor 6:16 and Rev 21:3 announce the covenant formula&rsquo;s eschatological completion.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The command to &ldquo;let your hands be strong&rdquo; grounds the imperative in the prophets who stood at the temple foundation-laying (520 BCE, the Haggai/Zechariah moment). Hearing the prophetic word is the prerequisite for courage. For Christians, Heb 3-4&rsquo;s sustained call to hold firm draws on exactly this logic: those who hear the Son must not harden their hearts as in the wilderness. The foundation is now Christ himself (1 Cor 3:11).</p>",
        "10": "<p>Before the restoration there was social chaos — no wages, no safety, neighbor set against neighbor. This is the Deut 28 covenant-curse condition (echoed in Haggai 1:6). Its Christological relevance: Jesus enters precisely this world of broken shalom to bear the consequences of the curse (Gal 3:13) and inaugurate its reversal. The contrast between v. 10 (former judgment) and vv. 11-12 (new era of blessing) mirrors the structure of Gal 3-4: formerly under curse, now under promise.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The new era begins: YHWH will no longer deal with the remnant as before. <em>Ke&rsquo;asher rishonim</em> (as formerly) marks a clean break. This is proto-eschatological &ldquo;new covenant&rdquo; language: not a reform of the old arrangement but a genuinely new mode of relation. Heb 8:13 explicitly says the Jeremianic new covenant renders the old &ldquo;obsolete&rdquo; — the same temporal rupture Zechariah registers here.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The seed of shalom (<em>zera&rsquo; ha-shalom</em>) produces cosmic fertility: vine, ground, sky, dew all cooperating. This reverses the Deut 28 curses of drought and blight and anticipates the eschatological fertility of Amos 9:13 (wine dripping from mountains). Jesus&rsquo; parable of the sower (Matt 13) and his vine-discourse (John 15:1-8) reframe this agricultural imagery Christocentrically: he is the vine, abiding in him produces the fruit of the new creation.</p>",
        "13": "<p>&ldquo;You have been a curse (<em>qelālāh</em>) among the nations&rdquo; describes Israel as a byword of disaster — nations swore curses invoking Israel&rsquo;s name. The reversal: &ldquo;you will be a blessing (<em>berākāh</em>).&rdquo; Paul reads the Abrahamic blessing/curse polarity through the cross: &ldquo;Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us&rdquo; (Gal 3:13-14), so that the blessing of Abraham might come to the Gentiles. Zechariah 8:13&rsquo;s reversal is Gal 3&rsquo;s argument in prophetic embryo.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The reminder of past judgment (&ldquo;I determined to bring disaster when your ancestors provoked me&rdquo;) is not meant to shame but to establish credibility for the promise of v. 15. Symmetrical faithfulness: YHWH was faithful to his word of judgment; he will be equally faithful to his word of restoration. Rom 11:22 uses the same logic: &ldquo;Note then the kindness and the severity of God.&rdquo; Both are grounded in covenant faithfulness.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The parallel construction with v. 14 pivots to good: &ldquo;so in these days I have determined again to do good.&rdquo; The word <em>yatav</em> (do good) counters the disaster of v. 14 point for point. This unconditional divine determination (&ldquo;I have determined&rdquo;) underlies the NT language of divine decree: Eph 1:9-10 speaks of the divine purpose (<em>eudokia</em>) to unite all things in Christ — a cosmic <em>yatav</em>.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Ethics for the new community: truth-speaking (<em>emet</em>) and just judgments (<em>mishpat emet ve-shalom</em>). These are not conditions for restoration but responses to it. The sequence mirrors the gospel: indicative (God restores) → imperative (therefore live this way). Jesus&rsquo; summary of the law in truth and love (John 14:6, 17; 1 John 4) and Paul&rsquo;s &ldquo;therefore&rdquo; ethics (Rom 12:1; Eph 4:1) follow the same grammar.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Three prohibitions: no plotting evil against neighbors, no love of false oaths. The term <em>shevuat shaqer</em> (false oath) points back to the Decalogue. Jesus&rsquo; Sermon on the Mount radicalizes exactly these commands: &ldquo;You have heard that it was said to those of old... but I say to you&rdquo; (Matt 5:21-48). The prohibition on false oaths appears explicitly at Matt 5:33-37 as Jesus redirects to simple truthfulness grounded in the new covenant heart.</p>",
        "18": "<p>A brief transitional messenger formula, marking the shift to a new oracle. The repeated divine speech formula across ch 8 signals the authoritative accumulation of promises — YHWH&rsquo;s word is reliable precisely because it is spoken. John 1:1 elevates this to its maximum: the Word of YHWH that came repeatedly to the prophets is now the eternal Logos become flesh, God&rsquo;s speech in its final and personal form.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The four mourning fasts (4th, 5th, 7th, 10th months) commemorated stages of Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall to Babylon (Jer 52:6-7, 12-13; 2 Kgs 25:3-4, 8-9, 25; 2 Kgs 24:1). Their transformation into joyful festivals signals that the grief of exile is reversible. Revelation&rsquo;s vision of the wedding supper of the Lamb (Rev 19:7-9) is the ultimate expression of this conversion of mourning into feasting, anticipated in Jesus&rsquo; table-fellowship and his self-identification as bridegroom (Mark 2:19-20).</p>",
        "20": "<p>An eschatological vision: peoples from many cities converging on Jerusalem. The centripetal force of restored Zion draws the nations, echoing Isaiah&rsquo;s vision of nations streaming to the mountain (Isa 2:2-4; 60:3). For the NT, the church as &ldquo;Jerusalem above&rdquo; (Gal 4:26) and the Spirit&rsquo;s Pentecost-gathering of diaspora Jews (Acts 2:5-11) inaugurate this ingathering, fulfilled cosmically in the nations walking by the light of the Lamb (Rev 21:24).</p>",
        "21": "<p>One city&rsquo;s inhabitants exhort another: &ldquo;Let us go immediately to seek the LORD&rsquo;s favor.&rdquo; The urgency (<em>hālok nelkāh</em>, lit. &ldquo;going let us go&rdquo;) conveys irresistible spiritual momentum. The NT word for &ldquo;seek the LORD&rdquo; is <em>zēteō</em>, used of the wise men (Matt 2:2), of seekers finding Jesus (John 1:38-39), and of the Father seeking true worshipers (John 4:23). The pilgrimage pattern is Christologically internalized: the temple is now Christ himself (John 2:21).</p>",
        "22": "<p>&ldquo;Many peoples and powerful nations&rdquo; — the word <em>&rsquo;ammim rabbim ve-goyim &rsquo;atzumim</em> emphasizes scale and political weight. This isn&rsquo;t merely diaspora Jews returning but foreign nations coming to seek YHWH. The Great Commission (Matt 28:18-20) is the missionary outworking of this vision: the risen Christ with &ldquo;all authority&rdquo; sends disciples to all nations. Paul cites Isaiah&rsquo;s servant-of-the-nations texts (Isa 49:6) as his mandate for Gentile mission (Acts 13:47); the same cosmic vision underlies Zechariah 8:22.</p>",
        "23": "<p>The climactic image: ten men from every nation gripping the robe of one Jew, saying &ldquo;God is with you.&rdquo; The number ten is symbolic fullness; &ldquo;every language&rdquo; echoes the Babel-reversal of Pentecost (Acts 2:6-11). The one Jew whose presence draws the nations is, typologically, the ultimate Israelite — Christ. <em>Immanuel</em> (God with us, Isa 7:14; Matt 1:23) is the name that answers the nations&rsquo; testimony &ldquo;God is with you.&rdquo; Eph 2:11-13 describes Gentiles who were &ldquo;far off&rdquo; brought near &ldquo;in Christ Jesus&rdquo; — the robe-seizing of Zech 8:23 actualized.</p>",
    },
    "9": {
        "1": "<p>The word <em>massa&rsquo;</em> (oracle/burden) introduces a new section — chapters 9-11, sometimes called Deutero-Zechariah. The oracle sweeps north to south through Aram, Phoenicia, and Philistia, recapitulating YHWH&rsquo;s judgment on the nations. The phrase &ldquo;the eyes of all humanity and of all Israel are fixed on the LORD&rdquo; sets the eschatological tone: universal attention converges on YHWH&rsquo;s action. The arc concludes in v. 9 with the coming king &mdash; the ultimate focus of all eyes. John 12:32 echoes this: &ldquo;I, when I am lifted up from the earth, will draw all people to myself.&rdquo;</p>",
        "2": "<p>Hamath on the northern horizon and Tyre and Sidon on the coast are proverbial for wisdom and power (Ezek 28 personifies Tyre&rsquo;s prince as the pinnacle of wisdom). Yet their cleverness does not preserve them from divine judgment. The NT parallel: &ldquo;Has not God made foolish the wisdom of the world?&rdquo; (1 Cor 1:20). Human wisdom and commercial power (Tyre = trading empire) are not ultimate; the kingdom that survives belongs to the humble king of v. 9.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Tyre&rsquo;s silver like dust and gold like mud depict extreme wealth — and extreme attachment to material security. The fortress (<em>matzor</em>) she builds for herself becomes ironic: the one who trusts in walls and wealth is most exposed. Jesus&rsquo; parable of the rich fool (Luke 12:16-21) and his warning about mammon (Matt 6:24) echo this irony. The wealth of Tyre passes; the kingdom of the meek king (v. 9) endures.</p>",
        "4": "<p>YHWH will dispossess Tyre and destroy her wealth. Alexander the Great&rsquo;s 332 BCE siege is commonly cited as historical fulfillment: he built a causeway using rubble thrown into the sea, technically fulfilling Ezek 26:12. The verse connects to a broader pattern: worldly power built on wealth and walls falls before YHWH&rsquo;s sovereign action. Rev 18&rsquo;s lament over Babylon/Rome recapitulates this judgment pattern in apocalyptic terms, anticipating the destruction of all economic empires opposed to God.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The Philistine cities &mdash; Ashkelon, Gaza, Ekron &mdash; tremble at Tyre&rsquo;s fall. Their reaction: terror, writhing, withered hope. The loss of Gaza&rsquo;s king signals political collapse. These coastal cities represent the residual Canaanite/Philistine opposition to Israel that has persisted since the conquest. Their judgment clears the way for the restored people under the coming king. Acts 8:26-40 places Philip&rsquo;s ministry to the Ethiopian eunuch on the Gaza road — the gospel reaches regions once under Philistine control.</p>",
        "6": "<p>A &ldquo;mixed people&rdquo; (<em>mamzer</em>, of uncertain etymology — possibly &ldquo;illegitimate mixing&rdquo; or simply &ldquo;foreigners&rdquo;) settles Ashdod as Philistia&rsquo;s pride is cut off. The mixed settlement signals ethnic dissolution: national identities that opposed Israel lose their coherence under divine judgment. This points forward to Pentecost&rsquo;s multinational gathering (Acts 2) and Paul&rsquo;s declaration that in Christ there is neither Jew nor Greek (Gal 3:28) — though the context there is inclusion, not judgment.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The remarkable promise: even the Philistines (<em>remnant of the Philistines</em>) can become &ldquo;like a clan within Judah,&rdquo; and Ekron like the Jebusites (incorporated into David&rsquo;s Jerusalem). Blood from their mouths and forbidden things from between their teeth may refer to dietary laws — their incorporation involves covenant conformity. This is the OT precedent for Gentile inclusion without ethnic erasure. Eph 2:19 declares former Gentiles &ldquo;no longer strangers and foreigners, but fellow citizens&rdquo; — the Jebusites-in-Jerusalem logic scaled to the world.</p>",
        "8": "<p>YHWH stations himself as a guard around his house so that no army passes through again. The phrase <em>ki &rsquo;attāh rā&rsquo;îtî beinay</em> (&ldquo;for now I am watching with my own eyes&rdquo;) is a sovereign claim of personal oversight. The &ldquo;no more passing through&rdquo; is reminiscent of the Passover: the destroyer passed over guarded houses. John 10:28-29 articulates the security theme Christocentrically: no one can snatch believers from Christ&rsquo;s hand or the Father&rsquo;s hand. The divine garrison is now the Good Shepherd.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The king of v. 9 disarms the war machine: chariot, war horse, battle bow are cut off. His reign is accomplished by disarmament, not conquest. <em>Ve-dibber shalom la-goyim</em> (&ldquo;he will speak peace to the nations&rdquo;) &mdash; the king&rsquo;s word is the instrument of universal peace. His dominion: &ldquo;from sea to sea, from the River to the ends of the earth&rdquo; echoes Ps 72:8 (the Solomonic ideal). Eph 2:14-17 identifies Christ as &ldquo;our peace,&rdquo; who by his cross broke down the dividing wall and &ldquo;preached peace to those who were far off and peace to those who were near.&rdquo;</p>",
        "11": "<p>&ldquo;Because of the blood of my covenant with you, I will free your prisoners from the waterless pit.&rdquo; The &ldquo;blood of the covenant&rdquo; (<em>dam beritekh</em>) echoes Exod 24:8 (Moses sprinkling covenant blood at Sinai) and is directly applied by Jesus at the Last Supper: &ldquo;This is my blood of the covenant&rdquo; (Matt 26:28; Mark 14:24). The waterless pit (<em>bor ein bo mayim</em>) recalls Joseph (Gen 37:24) and Jeremiah (Jer 38:6) — the type of rescue from death. Christ&rsquo;s resurrection is the ultimate liberation from the pit.</p>",
        "12": "<p>&ldquo;Return to the stronghold (<em>lā-bitzarôn</em>), you prisoners of hope.&rdquo; <em>Assirei ha-tiqvāh</em> (prisoners of hope) is a striking phrase: prisoners whose very captivity is oriented toward hope. The double restoration (&ldquo;I will restore double&rdquo;) echoes Job 42:10-12 and Isa 61:7. Jesus&rsquo; proclamation at Nazareth (Luke 4:18-19, citing Isa 61) — &ldquo;to set at liberty those who are oppressed&rdquo; &mdash; addresses exactly these prisoners of hope. The <em>bitzarôn</em> (stronghold/fortress) into which they return is now the refuge that is Christ (Ps 46; Heb 6:18-19).</p>",
        "13": "<p>YHWH bends Judah as a bow and makes Ephraim the arrow, wielded against the sons of Greece (<em>Yāvān</em>). Many scholars read this as a reference to the Maccabean resistance to Hellenism (167-164 BCE), making it one of the latest dateable allusions in the Prophets. Christologically, the conflict between covenant people and Hellenistic cultural pressure prefigures the church&rsquo;s struggle in a Greco-Roman world. Rev 19:11-15 depicts the return of Christ himself as the divine warrior — sword from his mouth replacing the bow and arrow of Zech 9:13.</p>",
        "14": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s theophanic appearance: he will appear (<em>yera&rsquo;eh</em>) over them, his arrow like lightning, the trumpet sounding, advancing in storm. This is the divine warrior storm theophany drawn from the exodus-Sinai tradition (Ps 18; Hab 3). Lightning and trumpet appear together in Sinai (Exod 19:16) and in the NT&rsquo;s parousia texts: &ldquo;For the Lord himself will descend from heaven with a cry of command, with the voice of an archangel, and with the sound of the trumpet of God&rdquo; (1 Thess 4:16; cf. Matt 24:31).</p>",
        "15": "<p>The LORD of Hosts shields his people; they devour their enemies and are &ldquo;full as a sacrificial basin, drenched like the corners of the altar.&rdquo; The imagery of altar-drenching evokes the slaughter offerings at the sanctuary. Paradoxically, the warriors become like priests offering sacrifice &mdash; the boundary between battle and liturgy dissolves. In Rev 19, Christ&rsquo;s victory is followed by &ldquo;the great supper of God&rdquo; (v. 17) &mdash; apocalyptic feast imagery that draws on this sacrificial-battle complex.</p>",
        "16": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD their God will save them as his people&rsquo;s flock.&rdquo; The shepherd-flock-saving complex culminates in the simile: they will &ldquo;gleam like gems (<em>avnei nezer</em>, coronation stones) in a crown over his land.&rdquo; The people become jewels in YHWH&rsquo;s crown &mdash; a royal image of dignity and worth. Mal 3:17 uses the same image (precious possession); 1 Pet 2:9 calls the church &ldquo;a royal priesthood, a holy nation&rdquo; &mdash; the crown-gem status of Zech 9:16 applied ecclesially. Eph 1:18 speaks of the riches of God&rsquo;s &ldquo;glorious inheritance in the saints.&rdquo;</p>",
        "17": "<p>The doxological close: &ldquo;How great is his goodness, how great is his beauty!&rdquo; (<em>mah tuvô umah yopiyô</em>). The goodness and beauty of YHWH overflow into agricultural blessing (grain, new wine), a synecdoche for total shalom. Ps 27:4 uses similar language for YHWH&rsquo;s beauty (<em>yophî</em>). In the NT, the beauty and goodness of God are revealed supremely in the face of Jesus Christ (2 Cor 4:6: &ldquo;the light of the knowledge of the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ&rdquo;). The eschatological feast (Rev 19:9; Matt 8:11) materializes the grain-and-wine blessing.</p>",
    },
    "10": {
        "1": "<p>Ask rain from YHWH at the season of the spring rain (<em>malkosh</em>, the late rain of March-April). The oracle redirects petitionary prayer from the household gods (v. 2) to YHWH as the one who makes storm clouds. The spring rain is also associated in Jewish interpretation with Messianic times (Joel 2:23 uses <em>malkosh</em> eschatologically). John 7:37-39, at the Feast of Tabernacles (which included a water-drawing ceremony), has Jesus cry: &ldquo;If anyone thirsts, let him come to me&rdquo; &mdash; re-directing the water-petition from ritual to person.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The household idols (<em>terāphim</em>) speak worthlessness (<em>aven</em>), diviners see false visions, dreamers tell lies. The result: the people wander like sheep without a shepherd (<em>k&rsquo;tzon yenu&rsquo;u ki-ein ro&rsquo;eh</em>). Matt 9:36 explicitly cites this image: seeing the crowds, Jesus &ldquo;had compassion on them because they were harassed and helpless, like sheep without a shepherd&rdquo; &mdash; the direct Christological identification of YHWH&rsquo;s promised shepherd with Jesus.</p>",
        "3": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s anger burns against the shepherds (leaders who exploit) and the leaders (<em>attudim</em>, he-goats &mdash; a standard leadership metaphor). But the same YHWH tends his flock and will make them like his majestic steed (<em>sus hod</em>) in battle. The contrast between exploitative shepherd-leaders and YHWH&rsquo;s faithful tending is developed in Ezek 34, which Jesus explicitly picks up in John 10. The shift from wandering sheep (v. 2) to battle horse (v. 3) depicts transformation through the true shepherd&rsquo;s care.</p>",
        "4": "<p>&ldquo;From him the cornerstone, from him the tent peg, from him the battle bow, from him every ruler.&rdquo; Four messianic images from the tribe of Judah. The <em>pinnāh</em> (cornerstone) is the foundational building stone; Ps 118:22 (the stone rejected becoming the cornerstone) is among the most cited OT texts in the NT: Matt 21:42; Acts 4:11; Eph 2:20; 1 Pet 2:7. The tent peg (<em>yātēd</em>) echoes Isa 22:23 (Eliakim as peg in a firm place, a type of Christ). Every ruler (<em>kol nogesh yachdāv</em>) points to the one from whom all legitimate authority derives.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The metaphors shift to battle: the people become warriors trampling the street mud, fighting because YHWH is with them. The shame of the horsemen (symbol of military power) parallels YHWH&rsquo;s disarming of the chariot and war horse in 9:10. The victory here is from Immanuel-presence (&ldquo;because the LORD is with them&rdquo;), not military superiority. The church&rsquo;s warfare in Eph 6:10-18 is similarly grounded in divine presence and the armor of God rather than worldly force.</p>",
        "6": "<p>Double restoration: house of Judah strengthened (<em>gibbartî</em>), house of Joseph saved (<em>ve-hoshatî</em>). The reunification of divided Israel is YHWH&rsquo;s sovereign act of compassion (<em>rihamtim</em>). The formula &ldquo;as though I had never rejected them&rdquo; describes total covenantal reinstatement. Paul&rsquo;s argument in Rom 11 &mdash; that the hardening of Israel is not final and that God has not abandoned his people &mdash; draws on exactly this framework: divine compassion and the faithfulness of the covenant-keeping God.</p>",
        "7": "<p>Ephraim (the northern kingdom tribes) will be like a warrior; their hearts will rejoice &ldquo;as with wine&rdquo; (<em>ki-libo yismach kayyayin</em>). The children will see and rejoice. This is the restoration of divided families across generations. The prodigal son&rsquo;s return (Luke 15:24: &ldquo;this my son was dead and is alive again&rdquo;) uses the same structure: the children rejoice because the lost one is found. Joy in the LORD (Phil 4:4) is the New Covenant fulfillment of the Ephraim-joy Zechariah envisions.</p>",
        "8": "<p>YHWH will signal (<em>eshtarqa&rsquo;</em>, whistle/hiss — as a shepherd calls sheep) and gather them, &ldquo;for I have redeemed them.&rdquo; The grounding of gathering in past redemption is crucial: the signal-call follows from the accomplished fact of redemption. In John 10:3-4, the Good Shepherd calls his own sheep by name and they follow his voice. The whistle/signal here becomes Christ&rsquo;s personal voice known to his sheep.</p>",
        "9": "<p>&ldquo;Though I scattered them among the nations, they will remember me in distant countries.&rdquo; Memory of YHWH in exile is not passive nostalgia but the beginning of return. The promise that children will survive and return anticipates the Gentile mission&rsquo;s paradoxical fruit: Jews scattered in the diaspora become the network through which Paul plants churches, and their children enter the messianic community. The <em>anamnēsis</em> (remembrance) of the Lord&rsquo;s Supper (Luke 22:19; 1 Cor 11:24-25) is the covenant-renewal act by which the gathered community enacts their &ldquo;remembering&rdquo; of their redeemer.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Return from Egypt and Assyria — the two historic oppressors of north and south — and settlement in Gilead and Lebanon until there is no room. The hyperbole of insufficent space (<em>lo yimmātze&rsquo; lahem</em>) echoes Isa 49:20 (the land too narrow for the restored children). Egypt and Assyria are symbolic poles; in Acts, the gospel moves from Jerusalem to Rome (east to west) gathering diaspora Jews and Gentiles. The fullness of the Gentiles coming in (Rom 11:25) is the hyperbolic-abundance language of Zech 10:10 applied to the eschatological community.</p>",
        "11": "<p>YHWH will pass through (<em>ya&rsquo;avor</em>) the sea of distress, striking the waves; the Nile dries up; Assyria is humbled; the scepter of Egypt departs. This is new-Exodus language: the sea-crossing and the end of the two imperial scepters. Matt 8:26-27 has Jesus rebuke the sea (&ldquo;Even the winds and the sea obey him&rdquo;) &mdash; the YHWH-sea-mastery theme applied to Christ. The fall of imperial scepters points toward Rev 11:15: &ldquo;The kingdom of the world has become the kingdom of our Lord and of his Christ.&rdquo;</p>",
        "12": "<p>The climactic promise: &ldquo;I will strengthen them in the LORD, and they will walk in his name.&rdquo; Walking in YHWH&rsquo;s name is covenant faithfulness (Mic 4:5). Strengthening (<em>gevartim</em>) echoes the Ephraim-warrior strength of v. 5-7. The NT equivalent: Phil 4:13 (&ldquo;I can do all things through him who strengthens me&rdquo;); 2 Tim 4:17 (&ldquo;the Lord stood by me and strengthened me&rdquo;). Walking in Christ&rsquo;s name (Col 2:6; John 14:6 — &ldquo;I am the way&rdquo;) is the Christological specification of walking in YHWH&rsquo;s name.</p>",
    },
    "11": {
        "1": "<p>The dirge-opening — Lebanon opens its doors for fire to devour its cedars — signals the wail section of chs 11-13. Cedar of Lebanon was the premier building timber; its destruction is used in Isa 14:8 and Ezek 31 as a judgment metaphor for the fall of empires. The sequence cedar-cypress-oaks (v. 2) describes a cascade of destruction. These wail-texts for fallen grandeur prefigure the lament over fallen Babylon (Rev 18:11-19: merchants weeping for lost luxury, including &ldquo;cedar&rdquo; in v. 12).</p>",
        "2": "<p>The cypress wails because the cedar has fallen; the oaks of Bashan lament the dense forest (<em>ya&rsquo;ar ha-batzur</em>). The ecological mourning anthropomorphizes the landscape: creation itself mourns the disruption of order. Rom 8:22 (&ldquo;the whole creation groans and labors&rdquo;) gives this motif its deepest NT expression. The fallen forest is not the end: the same creation awaits the revealing of the sons of God (Rom 8:19), and the tree of life (Rev 22:2) restores what the fallen cedars lost.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The cry of the shepherds whose glory is destroyed, and the roar of young lions in the Jordan jungle (<em>ga&rsquo;on ha-yarden</em>) — a rare reference to the riparian lion habitat. The shepherds and lions are both pride figures reduced to lamentation. The destruction of their pride (<em>shudad</em>) is YHWH&rsquo;s judgment. In the NT, the lion imagery shifts dramatically: Christ is both &ldquo;Lion of the tribe of Judah&rdquo; (Rev 5:5) and the lamb who was slain &mdash; the shepherd who does not wail over destroyed glory but willingly lays down his life (John 10:17-18).</p>",
        "4": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s command to Zechariah to shepherd &ldquo;the flock marked for slaughter&rdquo; (<em>tzon ha-haregāh</em>) launches the acted parable of the rejected shepherd (vv. 4-17). The prophetic role involves embodying the divine action symbolically. Jesus as the Good Shepherd was himself the lamb led to slaughter: Isa 53:7 (&ldquo;like a sheep led to the slaughter&rdquo;), cited in Acts 8:32-35 as fulfilled in Jesus&rsquo; passion. The shepherd who commands becomes the sheep who obeys unto death.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The flock&rsquo;s buyers slaughter them without guilt; the sellers praise YHWH for their profit; the shepherds show no mercy. This is a concentrated indictment of commercial exploitation of vulnerable people dressed in religious language (&ldquo;Praise the LORD — I have become rich!&rdquo;). Jesus&rsquo; temple-cleansing (Matt 21:12-13) directly addresses this corruption: &ldquo;My house shall be a house of prayer, but you have made it a den of robbers.&rdquo; The prophetic action cites Jer 7:11 but enacts Zech 11:5&rsquo;s scenario.</p>",
        "6": "<p>YHWH will no longer spare the inhabitants of the land; he will hand each one over to king and neighbor. The land becomes a mutual predation zone. This judgment oracle reflects the same theological logic as Rom 1:24-28 (YHWH &ldquo;gave them over&rdquo; to the consequences of their choices). The refusal of mercy here is not vindictiveness but the honoring of human choices: those who chose exploitation and rejected the covenant shepherd are left to the forces they have unleashed.</p>",
        "7": "<p>Zechariah takes the flock and two staffs: Favor (<em>No&rsquo;am</em>, pleasantness/grace) and Union (<em>Hovelim</em>, bonds/unity). This allegorical equipment represents YHWH&rsquo;s covenantal relationship with the nations (Favor = the covenant that restrained destructive forces) and the union between Judah and Israel. Good Shepherd Jesus names similar themes: John 10:16 (&ldquo;I have other sheep... and there will be one flock, one shepherd&rdquo;) is the Union-staff promise restated; &ldquo;I came that they may have life and have it abundantly&rdquo; (John 10:10) is the Favor-staff in action.</p>",
        "8": "<p>&ldquo;In one month I did away with three shepherds.&rdquo; The three shepherds are unidentified — commentators propose kings, offices (king/priest/prophet), or foreign overlords. The divine impatience with defective leadership reflects YHWH&rsquo;s zero tolerance for shepherds who harm the flock. Jesus similarly dismissed the religious leadership of his day as hirelings who flee when wolves come (John 10:12-13) and blind guides (Matt 23:16, 24). The <em>one month</em> compresses the judgment to signal its totality.</p>",
        "9": "<p>YHWH-through-Zechariah renounces the shepherding role: &ldquo;I will no longer shepherd you. What is dying, let it die.&rdquo; This is the hardening pattern of Rom 1: when a people persistently rejects divine care, YHWH eventually withdraws it. The three-fold &ldquo;let&rdquo; (&ldquo;let it die... let it be destroyed... let them devour one another&rdquo;) reflects the self-consuming nature of sin when left unchecked. Matt 23:38 (&ldquo;your house is left to you desolate&rdquo;) is Jesus&rsquo; application of the same verdict to Jerusalem.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Breaking the Favor staff cancels the covenant with all the peoples (<em>kol ha-&rsquo;ammim</em>). The restraint that protected Israel from the surrounding nations is lifted. The covenant of Favor was the grace that held back full judgment; its breaking is a solemn act. Heb 10:29 warns against those who trample the Son of God and profane the blood of the covenant — they despise what breaking the Favor-staff cost.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The sheep dealers watching understood this was the word of YHWH. The wretched/afflicted of the flock (<em>aniyyei ha-tzon</em>) who waited and watched received divine confirmation. This is the pattern of the remnant: the small group who recognize YHWH&rsquo;s word in prophetic action, while the larger group is indifferent. Jesus&rsquo; &ldquo;blessed are the poor in spirit&rdquo; (Matt 5:3) addresses exactly this spiritually attentive remnant.</p>",
        "12": "<p>&ldquo;If you think it right, pay me my wages; if not, keep them.&rdquo; The weighed-out price: <em>sheloshim keseph</em>, thirty pieces of silver. This was the indemnity for a slave killed by a goring ox (Exod 21:32) &mdash; a derisory sum for the divine shepherd&rsquo;s work. Matthew 27:9-10 cites this verse (attributing it to Jeremiah, perhaps from the broader prophetic scroll or a text-citation convention) as fulfilled when Judas returned the 30 silver pieces to the temple. The precise Matthean fulfillment is among the most directly typological in the Passion narrative.</p>",
        "13": "<p>&ldquo;Throw it to the potter&rdquo; &mdash; YHWH&rsquo;s sardonic command about this &ldquo;magnificent sum.&rdquo; The silver thrown (<em>tashlikh</em>) into the house of YHWH to the potter combines two motifs: prophetic action (Zechariah throws it) and prophetic irony (the glory attributed to the sum dissolves immediately). Matt 27:5-10 narrates the fulfillment precisely: Judas throws the silver into the temple (<em>tas naon</em>), the priests cannot put it back in the treasury and buy the potter&rsquo;s field instead. The two-step action mirrors the Zechariah text almost exactly.</p>",
        "14": "<p>Breaking the second staff (Union) cancels the brotherhood between Judah and Israel. The covenantal bond of national unity, already historically fractured since 722 BCE (Assyrian deportation of northern tribes), is formally renounced. In the NT, this fracture is not merely mourned but transcended: Eph 2:14-16 announces that Christ &ldquo;has broken down the dividing wall of hostility&rdquo; and created &ldquo;one new humanity&rdquo; from two. The Union-staff Christ wields is the cross.</p>",
        "15": "<p>YHWH commands Zechariah to take the gear of a foolish shepherd — to embody in prophetic performance what is coming next. This second role-enactment doubles the allegory: first the good shepherd rejected, now the bad shepherd raised up. The movement from faithful shepherd (vv. 4-14) to worthless shepherd (vv. 15-17) traces the historical transition from prophetic oversight to corrupt leadership. Jesus predicted false messiahs and false shepherds (Matt 24:24; John 10:10) who would come after his departure.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The worthless shepherd who will be raised up: does not care for the perishing, does not seek the straying, does not heal the injured, does not sustain the healthy — but devours the fat sheep and tears off their hooves. This is the inverse of every quality in the Good Shepherd (John 10:11-14; Ezek 34:4-5). The catalog of failures corresponds point-for-point to the good shepherd&rsquo;s duties. Christ is the perfectly positive image against which every exploitative leader is judged. The worthless shepherd of v. 16 is the anti-shepherd, whose coming is already implicitly a call to recognize the true one.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The woe-oracle on the worthless shepherd (<em>ro&rsquo;î ha-elil</em>): sword on his arm and right eye; arm withered, eye blinded. The sword that should protect the flock is turned on the shepherd himself; the eye that should watch over them is extinguished. This judicial punishment enacts the lex talionis of shepherding: fail to protect, and protection is withdrawn from you. Rev 19:20 describes the false prophet&rsquo;s destruction at the parousia. The contrast with the Good Shepherd who lays down his life (John 10:17-18) — voluntary sacrifice rather than involuntary judgment — is stark.</p>",
    },
    "12": {
        "1": "<p>The second <em>massa&rsquo;</em> (oracle/burden) introduces the eschatological diptych of chs 12-14. The triple creation-formula (&ldquo;who stretched out the heavens, laid the foundation of the earth, formed the human spirit within&rdquo;) grounds what follows in YHWH&rsquo;s cosmic sovereignty. The creator-God who made heaven, earth, and human spirit is fully competent to act in human history. John 1:3 (&ldquo;all things were made through him&rdquo;) identifies the Logos-Christ with the creation act invoked here, authorizing his eschatological role.</p>",
        "2": "<p>Jerusalem as a cup of reeling (<em>saf ra&rsquo;al</em>) for surrounding nations — those who drink from it stagger. The eschatological siege is a cup that intoxicates the besiegers. Jeremiah&rsquo;s cup-of-wrath imagery (Jer 25:15-28) and Rev 16:19 (&ldquo;Babylon was given the cup of the wine of God&rsquo;s fury&rdquo;) share this idiom. Jesus in Gethsemane prays about the &ldquo;cup&rdquo; (Matt 26:39) — he who drinks the cup of wrath himself so that Jerusalem need not be the staggering-cup for the world.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Jerusalem as a &ldquo;heavy stone&rdquo; (<em>even ma&rsquo;amasāh</em>) that injures all who try to lift it. The image shifts from cup to stone: those who attempt to move Jerusalem against divine will herniate themselves. This stone-that-injures motif links to the cornerstone of Ps 118:22 and Zech 10:4: the stone that injures those who handle it wrongly is the same stone that is the foundation for those who build on it correctly. 1 Pet 2:7-8 holds both together: for believers, the stone is precious; for unbelievers, &ldquo;a stone of stumbling and a rock of offense.&rdquo;</p>",
        "4": "<p>YHWH will strike the attacking nations&rsquo; horses with panic and their riders with madness, while watching over Judah. The divine targeting inverts the normal military advantage of cavalry. The phrase &ldquo;I will watch over the house of Judah&rdquo; (<em>ve&rsquo;al beit yehudāh epqach einay</em>) echoes the promise of Zech 9:8 (YHWH watching with his own eyes). The protecting gaze of God is a theme throughout the Psalms (Ps 121:4: &ldquo;he who keeps Israel will neither slumber nor sleep&rdquo;). Christ as the one who watches over his church (Matt 28:20: &ldquo;I am with you always&rdquo;) is the incarnate form of this promise.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The clans of Judah acknowledging that Jerusalem&rsquo;s inhabitants &ldquo;draw their strength from the LORD of Hosts, their God&rdquo; — a confession of source. This is not self-confidence but theocentric dependence. The specific formula &ldquo;their strength from YHWH of Hosts&rdquo; anticipates the NT call to &ldquo;be strong in the Lord and in the strength of his might&rdquo; (Eph 6:10). Zechariah&rsquo;s clans discover what Paul declares: human weakness is the venue for divine power (2 Cor 12:9-10).</p>",
        "6": "<p>The clans of Judah like a fire pot among logs, a flaming torch among sheaves — consuming the surrounding peoples. Fire as divine weapon in the hands of YHWH&rsquo;s people echoes Elijah&rsquo;s fire (1 Kgs 18) and anticipates the Pentecostal fire (Acts 2:3: tongues of fire). The gospel as consuming fire (Heb 12:29: &ldquo;our God is a consuming fire&rdquo;) spreads through proclamation. Jerusalem &ldquo;remains inhabited in its own place&rdquo; — the city endures while the surrounding powers are consumed.</p>",
        "7": "<p>YHWH saves the settlements of Judah first, lest the prestige of Jerusalem overshadow them. The deliberate reversal of priority (periphery before center) is a divine equity principle. Jesus embodies this principle: he ministers first to the margins (Galilee before Jerusalem, Samaritans, tax collectors, lepers) and enters Jerusalem last in his ministry. The last-first inversion of Matt 20:16 and the movement of Paul&rsquo;s mission from &ldquo;Jerusalem... to the end of the earth&rdquo; (Acts 1:8) both participate in this divine logic of reversal.</p>",
        "8": "<p>&ldquo;The weakest among them will be like David, and the house of David like God, like the angel of the LORD.&rdquo; The eschatological elevation is exponential: the weak become David-strong; the Davidic house becomes God-like/angel-like. The phrase <em>ke-elohim ke-mal&rsquo;akh YHWH lifneihem</em> (like God, like the angel of the LORD before them) echoes the tabernacle/conquest period when the angel of the LORD led Israel (Exod 23:20-23). Christ is simultaneously the weak one (Phil 2:7-8: taking the form of a servant) and the one at whose name every knee bows (Phil 2:10-11).</p>",
        "9": "<p>The divine commitment: &ldquo;I will set out to destroy all the nations that attack Jerusalem.&rdquo; <em>Biqqeshtî</em> (I will seek to destroy) — the language of determined divine pursuit. The reversal of the nations&rsquo; initiative: they come to attack; YHWH takes the offensive. Rev 19:11-21 depicts Christ returning on a white horse to defeat the nations assembled against the holy city. The promise of Zech 12:9 is fulfilled in apocalyptic scope at the parousia.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The mourning in Jerusalem will be &ldquo;as intense as the mourning for Hadad-rimmon in the plain of Megiddo.&rdquo; Hadad-rimmon is probably a place near Megiddo (or possibly a divine name invoked at a mourning rite). The mourning at Megiddo most likely refers to the lament over Josiah&rsquo;s death (2 Chr 35:24-25 records national mourning; Jer 22:10 alludes to it). Josiah, the greatest reforming king, cut down at the height of his reform — the paradigmatic grief for unjust loss of a righteous leader. The mourning of 12:10 (for the pierced one) is like grief for the righteous king prematurely cut off: a template for Passion mourning.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The mourning is organized by family divisions, husband and wife separately, each lineage privately. The enumerated families (Davidic, Nathanic, Levitic, Shimeite) cover royal, prophetic, priestly, and administrative streams. The breadth of the mourning (every family; every lineage) signals total societal grief. The account of the burial of Jesus involves women mourning (Luke 23:27-28) and the disciples scattered; John 19:25-27 has a small group at the cross. The universal mourning Zechariah envisions is the eschatological scope of what Calvary initiates.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The Levitical family and the Shimeite family mourn separately, with the women separately in each case. The Levites are the priestly tribe; Shimei is a subclan of Levi (Num 3:18). The specific enumeration of the priestly tribe as mourning is striking: the very lineage responsible for the temple cult mourns the pierced one. In the Passion account, after Jesus&rsquo; death &ldquo;the curtain of the temple was torn in two&rdquo; (Matt 27:51) — the priests&rsquo; world is upended. 1 Pet 2:9 reconstitutes the mourning priestly family as a &ldquo;royal priesthood.&rdquo;</p>",
        "14": "<p>All remaining families, each privately, with women separately. The totality phrase closes the mourning list: every lineage is implicated. No family is exempt from the grief. This comprehensive mourning reverses the sin of corporate indifference: the flock that was scattered (11:16-17) is now gathered in grief. Interestingly, the <em>separation</em> of men and women for mourning in the text may reflect both ritual propriety and the intensity of individual grief. The resurrection appearances — often first to women (Matt 28:1-10; John 20:11-18) — turn this grief to joy in a way that involves the women first.</p>",
    },
    "13": {
        "1": "<p>&ldquo;On that day a fountain will be opened (<em>tiqqāpēach maqqōr</em>) for the house of David and the inhabitants of Jerusalem to cleanse them from sin and impurity.&rdquo; The opened fountain for purification is one of the great OT images of atonement. Ezek 36:25 (&ldquo;I will sprinkle clean water on you&rdquo;) and Ps 51:7 (&ldquo;wash me, and I will be whiter than snow&rdquo;) share the purification motif. Rev 22:1 opens the river of the water of life flowing from the throne of God and the Lamb. John 19:34 notes that when the soldier pierced Jesus&rsquo; side, &ldquo;blood and water came out&rdquo; &mdash; a fountain-opening at the cross, connecting Zech 12:10 (piercing) and 13:1 (cleansing fountain) as sequential events.</p>",
        "2": "<p>YHWH will remove the names of idols from the land and eliminate false prophets along with the spirit of uncleanness (<em>ruach ha-tum&rsquo;āh</em>). Idols, false prophecy, and uncleanness form a triad of spiritual corruption. Acts 19:17-20 records idol-related books being burned in Ephesus at Paul&rsquo;s proclamation — a partial fulfillment. The eschatological cleansing goes further: Rev 21:27 says &ldquo;nothing unclean will ever enter&rdquo; the New Jerusalem. The Spirit of holiness (Rom 1:4: <em>pneuma hagiōsynēs</em>) counteracts the <em>ruach ha-tum&rsquo;āh</em> definitively in Christ.</p>",
        "3": "<p>False prophets will be killed by their own parents for lying in YHWH&rsquo;s name. The severity of the sanction (Deut 13:6-11 authorizes family members to execute false prophets) signals the absolute standard of prophetic truth. This is not an endorsement of the deathpenalty per se but a calibration: how seriously does YHWH take speaking falsely in his name? Jesus warns that false prophets who say &ldquo;Lord, Lord&rdquo; and perform signs will be rejected: &ldquo;I never knew you&rdquo; (Matt 7:22-23). The false-prophet problem Zechariah addresses finds its NT resolution in Jesus as the final and true prophet (Deut 18:18; Acts 3:22-23).</p>",
        "4": "<p>False prophets will be ashamed of their prophetic visions and will no longer wear the hairy cloak (<em>aderet se&rsquo;ar</em>) — the mark of a prophet (2 Kgs 1:8: Elijah; Matt 3:4: John the Baptist). Shame and self-concealment among false prophets in the day when true prophecy is vindicated. The hairy cloak appears in the NT most prominently on John the Baptist, who stands at the transitional moment: the last OT-style prophet pointing to the one who surpasses all prophets. After Christ, prophecy is both fulfilled (Matt 5:17) and transformed (1 Cor 12:10; Acts 2:17-18).</p>",
        "5": "<p>The former prophet disavows his prophetic identity: &ldquo;I am not a prophet. I am a farmer (<em>ish mekhareh adamāh</em>).&rdquo; The denial echoes Peter&rsquo;s denial (&ldquo;I am not&rdquo;, Matt 26:70-72) and Amos&rsquo;s own disclaimer (&ldquo;I am neither a prophet nor a son of a prophet; I am a shepherd and a dresser of sycamore figs,&rdquo; Amos 7:14). Amos&rsquo; self-distancing was authentic humility; the denial in Zech 13:5 is fearful self-protection. The contrast highlights what genuine prophetic calling looks like: not a professional identity to be defended, but a divine compulsion that carries cost.</p>",
        "6": "<p>&ldquo;What are these wounds on your hands (<em>makkat bein yadekha</em>, wounds between your hands)?&rdquo; The former prophet deflects: &ldquo;Wounds I received in the house of my friends.&rdquo; The wounds were likely cult-inflicted (1 Kgs 18:28: Baal prophets cutting themselves) or from ecstatic practice &mdash; evidence of false-prophet activity now shamefully concealed. The verse has classically been applied to Christ&rsquo;s nail wounds (the Passion typology is widely attested from early Christianity), though this was not the primary intention. Even as secondary typology it is significant: the one asked about wounds in his hands is the pierced one of 12:10, whose wounds are acknowledged at his return (Rev 1:7; John 20:27).</p>",
        "7": "<p>&ldquo;Awake, O sword, against my shepherd, against the man who is my associate (<em>&rsquo;amîtî</em>, my neighbor/close companion), declares the LORD of Hosts. Strike the shepherd so the sheep will be scattered.&rdquo; This is the most explicit NT-cited verse in chs 11-13: Jesus quotes it directly at Gethsemane (Matt 26:31; Mark 14:27: &ldquo;You will all fall away because of me tonight, for it is written, &lsquo;I will strike the shepherd, and the sheep of the flock will be scattered.&rsquo;&rdquo;). The shepherd is identified as YHWH&rsquo;s <em>&rsquo;amît</em> — uniquely close associate, near-kinsman — pointing toward the incarnate Son&rsquo;s unique relation to the Father. The scattering of the disciples at the arrest fulfills this precisely (John 16:32).</p>",
        "8": "<p>&ldquo;Throughout the whole land... two thirds shall be cut off and die, but one third will be left.&rdquo; The remnant-theology of two-thirds cut off and one-third surviving echoes Ezek 5:2, 12 (the thirds of Jerusalem&rsquo;s population). The proportion is a formal expression of judgment-with-remnant, not a precise numerical prediction. Rom 11&rsquo;s argument about Israel&rsquo;s partial hardening (&ldquo;a partial hardening has come upon Israel, until the fullness of the Gentiles has come in, and in this way all Israel will be saved,&rdquo; vv. 25-26) uses a similar logic: remnant election and eschatological restoration.</p>",
        "9": "<p>&ldquo;I will put that third through the fire and refine them as silver is refined, and test them as gold is tested.&rdquo; Refining through fire — the Malachi 3:3 imagery of the refiner&rsquo;s fire purifying the Levites — appears here as the destiny of the surviving remnant. Then the covenant renewal formula: &ldquo;They will call on my name, and I will answer them. I will say, &lsquo;They are my people,&rsquo; and they will say, &lsquo;The LORD is my God.&rsquo;&rdquo; 1 Pet 1:6-7 applies this refining metaphor to Christian suffering: &ldquo;the tested genuineness of your faith — more precious than gold that perishes though it is tested by fire.&rdquo; The covenant formula of v. 9b is the goal of all refinement: restored mutual belonging between YHWH and his people.</p>",
    },
}


def main():
    existing = load_comm("mkt-christ", "zechariah")
    merged = merge_comm(existing, ZECHARIAH)
    save_comm("mkt-christ", "zechariah", merged)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
